%N A397497 Primes in A397496, in order of appearance.
%C A397497 Also, an irregular array where each row is a (possibly empty) list of primes in row(n) of A397496.
%C A397497 a(322) in row 451 of A397496 has 1098 digits.
%H A397497 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397497/b397497.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..321</a>
%F A397497 {A397496(k) | A397496(k) is prime}.
%e A397497 Irregular triangle begins:
%e A397497   [empty row];
%e A397497   2;
%e A397497   3;
%e A397497   43;
%e A397497   5;
%e A397497   [empty row];
%e A397497   7;
%e A397497   [empty row];
%e A397497   [empty row];
%e A397497   109, 10987;
%e A397497   ...
%p A397497 T:= (n,k)-> parse(cat("",n-i$i=0..k-1)):
%p A397497 select(isprime, [seq(seq(T(n,k), k=1..n), n=1..47)])[];  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Jun 28 2026
%o A397497 (Python)
%o A397497 from sympy import isprime
%o A397497 def T(n, k): return int("".join(map(str, range(n, k-1, -1)))) # A397496
%o A397497 def row(n): return [tnk for k in range(n, 0, -1) if isprime(tnk:=T(n, k))]
%o A397497 print([e for n in range(1, 48) for e in row(n)])
